<i><color=\#FFA500>It's boring to wander aimlessly. If you concentrate your field of view </color><color=\#FFFF00><b>(Hold [Right-Click])</b></color><color=\#FFA500>, you can see past an object's otherwise normal sheen and spot its detective-worthy value.</color></i>
<i><color=\#FFA500>This is your </color><color=\#FFFF00>Detective Vision, </color><color=\#FFA500>and it is used to find clues and evidence to pin down suspects. Right now, you only need it to solve your current car predicament though.</color></i>
<i><color=\#FFA500>It's no use wandering around constantly holding it down, however. Most items need to fulfil a certain condition before they can be highlighted, as you will soon find out.</color></i>
<i><color=\#FFA500>Normally, you should be careful with how much you use it. During this time however, feel free to use it as much as you want to get a feel for it.</color></i>
<i><color=\#FFA500>Once you reach the crime scene and the actual investigation begins however, the recorded time of your Detective Vision will be factored in at the end of the case.</color></i>
<i><color=\#FFA500>If you ever need a refresher on your Detective Vision, consult your field manual by opening the pause menu using </color><color=\#FFFF00>[ESC].</color></i>
-> END